# CSS Grid in 5 Minutes

CSS Grid is the most powerful layout system in CSS. It lets you design **two-dimensional layouts** with rows and columns simultaneously.

## Quick Setup
```css
.container {
  display: grid;
  grid-template-columns: repeat(3, 1fr);
  gap: 1rem;
}
```

This creates a 3-column grid where each column takes equal space.

## The `fr` Unit
The `fr` (fraction) unit distributes available space proportionally:
- `1fr 2fr` → second column is twice as wide
- `repeat(auto-fill, minmax(200px, 1fr))` → responsive grid!

## Placing Items
```css
.item {
  grid-column: 1 / 3;  /* Span 2 columns */
  grid-row: 1 / 2;
}
```

> Grid handles the layout. You handle the content.

# TypeScript's Type System

TypeScript adds **static types** to JavaScript, catching bugs at compile time instead of runtime. It's JavaScript with a safety net.

## Basic Types
```typescript
let name: string = "Geeky";
let score: number = 42;
let active: boolean = true;
let items: string[] = ["a", "b"];
```

## Interfaces vs. Types
```typescript
interface User {
  id: string;
  name: string;
  score?: number; // optional
}

type Status = "active" | "inactive"; // union type
```

Both define shapes, but **interfaces** can be extended and merged; **type aliases** support unions and intersections.

## Generics: The Power Tool
```typescript
function first<T>(arr: T[]): T | undefined {
  return arr[0];
}
```

Generics let you write **reusable, type-safe** code that works with any type.

## Utility Types
- `Partial<T>`: Makes all properties optional
- `Pick<T, K>`: Selects specific properties
- `Omit<T, K>`: Excludes specific properties
- `Record<K, V>`: Creates an object type with key-value pairs

> Types are documentation that the compiler can verify.

# CSS Animations That Delight

CSS animations bring interfaces to life. When done well, they **guide attention**, provide **feedback**, and make interactions feel natural.

## Transitions: The Quick Win
```css
.button {
  background: #3b82f6;
  transition: background 0.3s ease, transform 0.2s ease;
}
.button:hover {
  background: #2563eb;
  transform: scale(1.05);
}
```

Transitions animate between **two states** when a property changes.

## Keyframe Animations
```css
@keyframes fadeSlideIn {
  from {
    opacity: 0;
    transform: translateY(20px);
  }
  to {
    opacity: 1;
    transform: translateY(0);
  }
}

.card {
  animation: fadeSlideIn 0.4s ease-out;
}
```

Keyframes give you **full control** over multi-step animations.

## Performance Golden Rules
- Only animate **transform** and **opacity** (GPU-accelerated)
- Avoid animating `width`, `height`, `top`, `left` (triggers layout)
- Use `will-change` sparingly to hint the browser

## Timing Functions
- `ease-out`: Fast start, gentle finish (entering elements)
- `ease-in`: Slow start, fast finish (exiting elements)
- `cubic-bezier()`: Custom curves for unique personality

> Motion is the soul of interface design.
